{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:17:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15008"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15008"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.17,0.12,0.33,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7696"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52204"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5257"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18809"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECephalosporins are beta-lactam antibiotics that are classified into different generations based on their spectrum of activity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a fourth-generation cephalosporin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cefazolin","Cefuroxime","Cefotaxime","Cefepime","Cephalexin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe different generations of cephalosporins are characterised by their antimicrobial spectrum and resistance to beta-lactamases:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefazolin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecephalexin\u003C/strong\u003E are first-generation cephalosporins with good gram-positive coverage but limited gram-negative activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefuroxime\u003C/strong\u003E is a second-generation cephalosporin with improved gram-negative coverage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefotaxime\u003C/strong\u003E is a third-generation cephalosporin with enhanced gram-negative coverage and moderate gram-positive activity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECefepime\u003C/strong\u003E is a fourth-generation cephalosporin with broad-spectrum activity against both gram-positive and gram-negative organisms, including \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E, and enhanced stability against beta-lactamases\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cephalosporins are classified into generations based on their spectrum of antimicrobial activity and resistance to beta-lactamases","Fourth-generation cephalosporins like cefepime have the broadest spectrum of activity against both gram-positive and gram-negative bacteria","Each successive generation of cephalosporins generally has improved gram-negative coverage but may lose some gram-positive activity"],"references":["Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Bona, C. A., \u0026 Bonilla, F. A. (2019). Textbook of immunology. CRC press","Yahav D, Paul M, Fraser A, Sarid N, Leibovici L. Efficacy and safety of cefepime: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Lancet Infect Dis. 2007 May;7(5):338-48. doi: 10.1016/S1473-3099(07)70109-3. PMID: 17448937."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52204"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15008"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52204"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T21:05:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T22:00:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7696"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66750"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":nu